{{Rail-transport-stub}}
{{law stub}}

In the [[ecclesiastical law]] of the [[Church of Scotland]], the '''Barrier Act''' of 1697 is a measure which compels the [[General Assembly of the Church of Scotland|General Assembly]] to consult the wider Church before innovating in the areas of worship, doctrine, discipline or church government.<ref>[http://www.law.cf.ac.uk/clr/networks/Church%20of%20Scotland.pdf Church of Scotland], Cardiff Law School</ref>

It is a provision which prevents the General Assembly from making core innovations which might profoundly affect the [[ecclesiastical polity|polity]] of the church without first referring these to the presbyteries.  A matter which falls under the Barrier Act must first be passed by the General Assembly, then be referred in the form of an ''overture'' to the [[Presbytery (presbyterian church)|presbyteries]] and ratified by a majority of these, before being returned to the General Assembly of the following year and passed again there.  This is intended to prevent rash decisions to the long-term detriment of the church.  Important matters which fell under the Barrier Act in recent years include the [[Ordination of women in the Church of Scotland|ordination of women]], which was passed in the 1960s, and the proposed union with the [[Scottish Episcopal Church]], which failed to receive the support of the presbyteries in the 1980s.<ref>[http://www.churchofscotland.org.uk/about_us/church_law/barrier_act The Barrier Act 1697], Church of Scotland</ref> 

